We need your support to keep J-I going. For years, J-I has been sustained almost entirely by a small group of dedicated volunteers who have spent thousands of dollars out of their own pockets to send books, commissary, letters, and a well-received newsletter to prisoners. Unfortunately, due to rising costs, we may no longer be able to continue producing the newsletter without your help. If you would like to contribute to keeping the newsletter alive and ensuring we can continue sending books to prisoners, donations can be made to a Monero account set up by a volunteer. We have ambitious plans to expand our outreach, but financial limitations are holding us back. We regularly receive letters from other White inmates who have read the newsletter and want to receive their own copies. Printing hundreds of pages and purchasing stamps is costly, and as political persecution increases, so do our expenses. Our goal is to reach as many White inmates as possible, regardless of whether they are political prisoners. In the past, J-I volunteers have also provided clothing and essentials to recently released inmates. With more resources, we would love to continue this important work. Offering basic items like work clothes, shampoo, soap, and razors makes a huge difference to those who have nothing when they get out. Its one less burden for them to bear as they rebuild their lives. If you believe in the ideals of our cause, supporting our brothers and sisters who have sacrificed their freedom for our struggle is crucial. Ensuring they are not forgotten is one of the most meaningful ways to show your commitment. PAxAC on Tour - Hungary 2024  In March, two members from Pennsylvania Active Club went on tour to Europe. This included a visit to Hungary and the great city of Budapest. Prior to our trip we admittedly had little knowledge of this proud country's thousand year history. Needless to say we were blown away and humbled by the accomplishments, perseverance, and brilliance of the Hungarian people. It is safe to say we gained a new level of admiration and respect for them. Upon arrival we were greeted by friends and comrades whom we had yet to meet in person. We shared some excellent food and ideas and the paprika really spiced things up  During one day, for more than eight hours we took in as much of the incredible culture within Budapest thanks to some really great people who know their history.  One of the biggest highlights was getting to participate in a training session with members of Lgi Hungria. All of these men were very skilled and shared tips and pointers. What was most impressive was the level of respect and professionalism displayed by everyone who participated. You welcomed us into your home and treated us like family and for this we are eternally grateful. While our stay in Hungary was brief and there remains much to see, this was an experience we will not forget. We look forward to returning again someday. We are proud to call you all brothers and if you ever visit the USA, you have a home here in Pennsylvania. ACTIVE CLUBS Q: "Is is not equally good to just train at a regular MMA-gym?" A: The essential difference is that in an Active Club you are training with guys with whom you share a greater vision, and thus the camaraderie goes beyond just training (i.e. you are on the same side in a struggle that is much larger than any single individual). Therefore, the training takes on a greater metaphysical aspect. When you are training at an MMA-gym in Gotham City, you will, of course, also gain metaphysical benefits (challenging and overcoming yourself, pushing yourself to the limit etc.) as well as physical benefits (being physically fit and knowing how to fight). When you train with your Mnnerbund, however, you are also training and building a whole group. If you know that you may perhaps one day rely on an individual having your back, you will want that individual to be as sharp as possible. The same cannot be said about a stranger at an MMA-club. I have trained plenty in both environments, and it is often necessary to train at regular clubs. The philosophy is beautiful in its simplicity: get good training and experience in the regular clubs  then share that experience when you train with your guys. Moreover, it is highly satisfactory to share your knowledge with younger guys that are on our own side during training sessions like this. Truly a good feeling. Lastly, on a personal note, I appreciate the action-oriented and pan-European vibes of Active Clubs. Great stuff!

Hey man. I want you to hear it from me first. Jasons dead. Silence for a moment. I waited for my old platoon sergeant to say it was a joke. I had just had a conversation with Jason the day before online. We had complained to each other about how lonely our society was for men who had spent years sweating, crying and bleeding alongside each other. About how soft the so-called men we worked alongside as civilians were. About how society in general had no place left for warriors. Jason wasnt dead. He was having a hard time, but we all were right? I didnt want you to see it online. His family is going to have the service this week. They wanted us to feel free to come for a memorial service over the holiday weekend this month. I thanked my old sergeant and hung up the phone. Leaned over my kitchen countertop and let the emotions wash over me. For the first time in a long time, I sobbed. At the memorial service, a dozen-odd roughly dressed men made a circle in the church parking lot. Cigarettes and beers passed covertly. We recounted memories, stories and conversations with Jason. Every one of us could remember a time we depended on him for something; a mood lift, a joke, our sanity or even our lives. Jason was a year shy of thirty. He left behind a grieving girlfriend, heartbroken parents and a brother who blamed himself. He left behind a group of men who had laughed and cried and fought with (and against) him. He was the first of the men I had forged a bond in fire with to pass on from wounds not of his body but his spirit. The first, but not the last. Ive been asked what radicalized me. It wasnt the time five black males beat me to the ground until I passed out before they went through my pockets. It wasnt the time two hispanic boys held guns at my head and took my phone, backpack and wallet. It wasnt the time I had a frozen water bottle and a beer can lobbed into the back of my head at a political event where I went without being a supporter, just wanting to hear out a candidate. It was the looks on my brothers faces as the rifles fired over a flag-draped casket. It was the despair I saw in a dozen war-worn White faces as men watched a brother laid to final rest, born down by the weight of a world who rejected his very existence. Our opponents love to paint our movement as one of hatred, of reactionary opposition to difference. The reality is, our fight is one of love for our racial brothers and sisters. Of honor for our forefathers who secured our future through their labor and pain. Of hope for our children, and the future we shall leave as their inheritance. We dont fight because we hate those different from us. We fight because we love our own Folk. One Folk. One Nation. Hail victory!

If you look good you do good and if you do good, we win! Take care and be the best. You will thank yourself later.

Fauna of Columbia  American Black Bear (Ursus Americanus) Once ubiquitous and found across the continental United States, the American Black Bear has been extirpated from much of its historic range and has since been relegated to remote forests and sparsely-habitated regions. Well-known for their long hibernations, black bears sustain themselves through the spring to fall with an omnivorous diet consisting of vegetation, berries, carrion, and fish. Found in a range of colors including white, blonde cinnamon, brown, and black, they are often mistaken for their cousin the Grizzly Bear. "It seems strange that bears, so fond of all sorts of flesh, running the risks of guns and fires and poison, should never attack men except in defense of their young. How easily and safely a bear could pick us up as we lie asleep!"  John Muir, My First Summer in the Sierra, 1911 Grand Teton National Park, Wyoming

A friend of mine pointed out recently that, while annoying and unjust in the case of the Honorable Mr. Blevins, recall elections are an excellent way to bring immediate and targeted political pressure to bear on local politicians. Their signature requirements are typically low (20% or less of total votes cast is not unusual) and even the initiation of the process forces the politico in question to devote campaign resources to fighting the recall. The process usually goes something like this: not more than 6 months before or less than 6 months after an election, a voter(s) must file an affidavit with the county or municipal clerk petitioning a recall. The clerk draws up the papers and an announcement is made. The petitioner(s) then have a set amount of time to get signatures from REGISTERED voters and present them to the clerk, at which point a special recall vote is scheduled. From the side of the petitioner, this requires >A non-room temperature IQ >A few hundred dollars in Kinko's fees to print petition forms (sometimes the clerk will do it for you, but you will usually need more) >Organizational skills >A fiery hatred of the shit bag in question that keeps you knocking doors for six weeks to get your signatures All of which can be accomplished by a handful of devoted people who want to make a tangible difference in the way their community is governed. An Open Letter to NJP Supporters: Where do I even begin? I guess I'd like to start by saying this is coming from a place of sincerity. Seeing as White Nationalism is poisoned by irony, hyper combvativeness, and catty passive aggressiveness. If you were a supporter or a volunteer for the NJP, I'm sorry. I truly am. You worked hard and risked a lot, and some of you lost a lot. Be it time, money, reputation, a job, what have you. The one consistent thing I see among the former supporters of the NJP is that they all lost trust. And that is the most devastating. I don't need to tell you we as a collective are under attack. What just happened has ensured that good people, people who are willing to give time, money, and show their face in public, will never touch our politics again. Those qualities are rare and so desperately needed for our struggle, especially in the next few years. I'm reminded of 2017. And it feels like we are all in this same spot again. We are disorganized, nobody trusts each other, and everyone just wants to retreat into chat rooms on telegram. For those who weren't supporters, you may feel the impulse to attack and jump on NJP supporters. "Yeah, that's what you get for trusting a bunch of podcasters!" I know you guys invested a lot, especially in Ohio. It couldn't have gotten as far as it did without you guys. Please contact us, let's let by gones be by gones, and work together. Hey man. I want you to hear it from me first. Jasons dead. Silence for a moment. I waited for my old platoon sergeant to say it was a joke. I had just had a conversation with Jason the day before online. We had complained to each other about how lonely our society was for men who had spent years sweating, crying and bleeding alongside each other. About how soft the so-called men we worked alongside as civilians were. About how society in general had no place left for warriors. Jason wasnt dead. He was having a hard time, but we all were right? I didnt want you to see it online. His family is going to have the service this week. They wanted us to feel free to come for a memorial service over the holiday weekend this month. I thanked my old sergeant and hung up the phone. Leaned over my kitchen countertop and let the emotions wash over me. For the first time in a long time, I sobbed. At the memorial service, a dozen-odd roughly dressed men made a circle in the church parking lot. Cigarettes and beers passed covertly. We recounted memories, stories and conversations with Jason. Every one of us could remember a time we depended on him for something; a mood lift, a joke, our sanity or even our lives. Jason was a year shy of thirty. He left behind a grieving girlfriend, heartbroken parents and a brother who blamed himself. He left behind a group of men who had laughed and cried and fought with (and against) him. He was the first of the men I had forged a bond in fire with to pass on from wounds not of his body but his spirit. The first, but not the last. Ive been asked what radicalized me. It wasnt the time five black males beat me to the ground until I passed out before they went through my pockets. It wasnt the time two hispanic boys held guns at my head and took my phone, backpack and wallet. It wasnt the time I had a frozen water bottle and a beer can lobbed into the back of my head at a political event where I went without being a supporter, just wanting to hear out a candidate. It was the looks on my brothers faces as the rifles fired over a flag-draped casket. It was the despair I saw in a dozen war-worn White faces as men watched a brother laid to final rest, born down by the weight of a world who rejected his very existence. Our opponents love to paint our movement as one of hatred, of reactionary opposition to difference. The reality is, our fight is one of love for our racial brothers and sisters. Of honor for our forefathers who secured our future through their labor and pain. Of hope for our children, and the future we shall leave as their inheritance. We dont fight because we hate those different from us. We fight because we love our own Folk. One Folk. One Nation. Hail victory!

An Open Letter to NJP Supporters: Where do I even begin? I guess I'd like to start by saying this is coming from a place of sincerity. Seeing as White Nationalism is poisoned by irony, hyper combvativeness, and catty passive aggressiveness. If you were a supporter or a volunteer for the NJP, I'm sorry. I truly am. You worked hard and risked a lot, and some of you lost a lot. Be it time, money, reputation, a job, what have you. The one consistent thing I see among the former supporters of the NJP is that they all lost trust. And that is the most devastating. I don't need to tell you we as a collective are under attack. What just happened has ensured that good people, people who are willing to give time, money, and show their face in public, will never touch our politics again. Those qualities are rare and so desperately needed for our struggle, especially in the next few years. I'm reminded of 2017. After Charlottesville (who had many of the same organizers oddly enough), everyone had essentially stepped back from demonstrations or even meeting in real life at all. For those who weren't supporters, you may feel the impulse to attack and jump on NJP supporters. "Yeah, that's what you get for trusting a bunch of podcasters!" It's not as if many of us haven't been a part of now defunk organizations. If you were a volunteer for the NJP, we need you. Your people need you. ACTIVE CLUBS Q: "Is is not equally good to just train at a regular MMA-gym?" A: The essential difference is that in an Active Club you are training with guys with whom you share a greater vision, and thus the camaraderie goes beyond just training (i.e. you are on the same side in a struggle that is much larger than any single individual). Therefore, the training takes on a greater metaphysical aspect. When you are training at an MMA-gym in Gotham City, you will, of course, also gain metaphysical benefits (challenging and overcoming yourself, pushing yourself to the limit etc.) as well as physical benefits (being physically fit and knowing how to fight). When you train with your Mnnerbund, however, you are also training and building a whole group. If you know that you may perhaps one day rely on an individual having your back, you will want that individual to be as sharp as possible. The same cannot be said about a stranger at an MMA-club. I have trained plenty in both environments, and it is often necessary to train at regular clubs. The philosophy is beautiful in its simplicity: get good training and experience in the regular clubs  then share that experience when you train with your guys. Moreover, it is highly satisfactory to share your knowledge with younger guys that are on our own side during training sessions like this. Truly a good feeling. Lastly, on a personal note, I appreciate the action-oriented and pan-European vibes of Active Clubs. Great stuff!

One of the club's objectives is to fill its ranks with quality members or make quality members out of them. This is why your recruitment tactics and club aesthetics are crucial because what you put out is what you will attract. I have often seen new clubs start looking to go as extreme as possible to garner as much attention as possible. Doing this usually seems to bring guys that are attention seekers or have more of an anti-social background. The problem when your club does this approach to be as edgy as possible is first for recruitment you will only ever get guys that are already into this shock and awe style which many times leaves guys burnt out of chasing the "high" from getting first coverage of the group and then having to constantly be edgier and edgier as they try to get back that "high" (such as what happened to national action). When your club is just starting, the main task should be laying down the groundwork and building a tight-knit club that will be able to weather future storms. Having serious attention on your club will only make things much harder, and if law enforcement is involved, it can halt everything. For example, on my travels across Europe, I stayed in one country for a few months. The local nationalists were not so organized and scattered across different football clubs, bars, and gyms, there was nothing cohesive but there was plenty of potential . So they formed a club within a week. They got around 50 guys. Instead of having some training or hikes, etc., to get to know one another better or discuss tactics and bring in more people silently growing the ranks, they wanted to announce their new club with a bang. The first night they get all 50 guys together, and go to an Antifa bar and graffiti all over smash out the windows, then they went to some communist statues in the city and vandalized them. Of course, they made a proper film of the action which was all great when it was shared and lots of people liked the video, and for sure overnight they became a big name in the city. (It would also suggest not putting anything that can be taken as an illegal activity when promoting video.) The media took to it as well making it a huge story over the vandalization of the statues. Like always, the media put pressure on the police to get involved. The police came down hard and raided 15 guys' houses in the middle of the night. What was a promising club with already 50 guys was finished after just doing one action. Because the club had no time to build a good foundation and form a bond between members to put in proper leadership and plan B it was over as fast as it started. It is better to start small, with small actions to test the club's strength before taking on a bigger role. Focus on building a strong core before looking to grab a five-minute headline in some bugmans article.
